BA2479/2: Dam sinking ripper, possibly Worsley Johnston (my father) wielding the stick and Arthur Clark operating the ripper.
BA2479/3: Driver operating this rig and machine could be John (Jack) Howard Clark (my uncle) at Glen Lowan, Kulin, mid-1920s
BA2479/4: Unloading wheat ready for bag sowing, Kulin. Possibly my parents, Worsley and Margaret (nee Clark) Johnston, and Jack Clark.
BA2479/5: An eight-horse team pulling a dam sinking ripper, probably Glen Lowan, Kulin
BA2479/6: Channel, excess soil removed prior to the next rip, Kulin (?)
BA2479/7: Scoop almost full of soil in preparation for emptying.
BA2479/8: Large stack of hay in the vicinity of Kulin railway siding, early to mid 1920s
BA2479/9: Hay stack at Kulin railway siding
BA2479/10: Horse drawn sully ready to go into Kulin. The gentleman on the left could be Jack Clark (my uncle)
BA2479/11: Football team possibly at Kulin, mid 1920s. Jack Clark (?) in white, back row, third from right.
BA2479/12: Flooded lean-to building, possibly Glen Lowan, Kulin, mid 1920s, with Arthur Clark (?) my grandfather.
BA2479/13: Wagon load of bagged wheat and 4 horse team, possibly on Glen Lowan, Kulin, 1920s
BA2479/14: I would say that this is myself taken at Kulin, WA between 1926 and 1928. The guard dog, Bully, which was given to the parents as a wedding present is not impressed with the toy pussy.
BA2479/15: Bully is not long out of his bath. I can well remember being bathed in these tubs as a child.
BA2479/16: This photo could have been taken in Kulin after the parents were married. Mum is feeding Bully and Kitten whilst holding a lamb with her left arm.
BA2479/17: Bully on the chain. He seems to have been doing some scratching probably to exercise his paws.
BA2479/18: This picture shows Mum holding me not long after I was born, possibly about 6 months.

BA2479/19: A group of Kulin footballers. Taken possibly in the early 20's at Kulin WA. Uncle Jack Clark is in the back row, 6th from the right. He had his muscles ripped out of his left arm whilst playing football during his school days.
BA2479/20: This photo shows Dad clearing country using a home made scrub roller. There are possibly six horses in the team. He is riding the rear horse on the right of the photo.
BA2479/21: This is another photo of Dad. He was probably about to go into Kulin when this photo was taken.

BA2479/22: Bob and myself on a swing- possibly at Konjonolocking. Not long after this photo was taken, Dad left Kulin in order to take up a position as Agricultural Instructor for the SA department of Agriculture. He was based at Riverton.

BA2479/23: This photo shows a possibly disused house on the right hand side of the Kulin to Narrogin Road. It would have been about 1km out of the town. As far as I am aware this could be the cottage where my parents were living in Kulin while Dad was clearing a far
BA2479/24: Wheat crop, Kulin, WA. Gentleman is probably EB Johnston, for whom Dad developed a property.
BA2479/25: J.H. Clark inspecting ration sheep, Glen Lowan, Kulin, WA. Photo was probably taken in 1925.

BA2479/26: In this photo I am on top of the roof at a property known as Glen Lowan. A freak windstorm occurred and bent the shed roof over as can be seen from the photo. I am on the roof and Uncle JH Clark is sitting on the ladder. Prior to the storm blowing all of

BA2479/27: The Manager's residence at Rawlinna station. For the 1982 Christmas lunch all of the station hands, the junior overseer, the station hands' cook and her husband and family were invited to the Manager's residence where each person received a little gift.
BA2479/28: A distant view of the homestead taken from the windmill which supplied water to the homestead, station hands' quarters, as well as the Overseer's and Mechanic's residence.
BA2479/29: For this view of the station hands' quarters I climbed up to the platform of the windmill which supplied water to all of the homes on the northern side of the station.
BA2479/30: Whilst on the platform I took 2 shots of the station hands' quarters. My room was on the right hand side of the white door on the right hand side of the photos.
BA2479/31: One time the younger lads asked me to dress up in overalls and broad brimmed hat. One of them took the photo. It was taken outside my room. This photo is the result.
BA2479/32: Crutching shed at Rawlinna. This shed was situated about 1km south east of the homestead.

BA2479/33: This was the Toyota which was supplied to me for the Netting Rider's job. It was a petrol driven vehilcle which had a 4 cylinder engine. Whilst the vehicle which had a comfortable cabin the fuel consumption left a lot to be desired.

BA2479/34: One time I was returning to the homestead towards conclusion of a trip. I was driving from west to east along the Kalgoorlie to Rawlinna Road. Suddenly there was a yell and loud tapping noise on the cabin roof, "Howard. Come and give me a hand. My vehicle
BA2479/35: I always took my camera out on the job. Another item of equipment in my vehicle was a pair of binoculars. This sunset looked interesting so it was photographed. This photo was the result.

BA2479/36: After I had been at Rawlinna station for about 3 months a Gymkhana was organised in the town. Quite a few of the lads from Rawlinna station took part including the gentleman wearing number 8 on his back.
BA2479/37: About half way as one drove south on the station there was an outstation known as Depot. This was where the shearing was done. The photo shows the homestead at Depot.

BA2479/38: An outside view of the shearing shed at Depot. There were 16 stands, 8 on the eastern side of the shed and 8 on the western side. I was told that three persons were employed picking up fleeces of wool.
BA2479/39: Two people skirting fleece on a skirting table during shearing. This process is done to remove foreign matter such as sweat glands from the fleece.
BA2479/40: The machinery and maintenance shed at Depot. My vehicle is facing towards the enterance of the shed.
BA2479/41: These outbuildings at Depot are from left to right, the hearers' mess room, shearer's quarters and the station hands' quarters.

BA2479/42: These buildings were taken at Moonera when I called here for supplies and petrol. The buildings are from left to right, Overseer's residence, station hand's quarters and the Manager's residence. The photo was taken looking north to south.
BA2479/43: Railway worker's cottages situated at a siding known as Zanthus which is about 200kms east of Kalgoorlie. This photo was taken from the Perth bound train.
BA2479/44: Paddy Hannan's statue, Kalgoorlie Railway Station. On the right hand side of the statue there is a replica of a waterbag so that people can have a drink of water.

BA2479/45: This photo of the cottage at Miling was where six of us slept in 1949. On the right of the photo I am cleaning my club rifle. The motor cycle in the belonged to me. Miling would be about 100kms north of Perth and the farm where I worked was about half way

BA2479/46: Drive through shed at the farm where I worked in 1949. Fertilizer was kept in the shed, and shearing was done. During seeding some of the farmworkers, myself included slept in this shed after a night spent driving the tractor.

BA2479/47: This photo of myself was taken on some country which had not long been burnt ready for the first crop. I am mounted on a horse named Seldom. The gentleman on the left of the photo was the foreman Mr T Larkin.

BA2479/48: On one occasion the employer wanted a dam sunk in a paddock neat the western boundary of the farm. He'd engaged a dam sinking contractor who had a dam sinking plant consisting of a TD18A international tractor and other equipment. The photo shows the plant

BA2479/49: A load of Glen Lowan wool ready to be taken into Kulin for sale in a wool store. The people in the picture are from left to right, BHW Johnston, JH Clark and an employee from the neighbouring farm. The photo was taken in 1950.

BA2479/50: During the first year I was in Kulin it was decided that the town should have its own water supply. A dam sinking contractor was hired for the job. The photo shows a Caterpillar D7 tractor hauling a large capacity scoop. After the job was done I was given

BA2479/51: Early in 1951 Glen Lowan was sold. I landed a job with another farmer who lived about 25kms east of Kulin. He bought a Chamberlain 40KA wheel tractor in 1951. This photo of myself backing an AL haverstor into the storage shed after harvest was not easy.

BA2479/52: This employer owned an International TD35 International Crawler Tractor similar to the machine I drove at Miling. The machine in the photo was an earlier model that the machine I drove at Miling.

BA2479/53: Early in 1952 the employer cut sufficient hay to make about 5000 bales. All of these bales had to be carted into a small paddock in the vincinity of the shearing shed. The photo shows the bale loader mounted on the International truck. One man drove and t

BA2479/54: The completed stack ready to be waterproofed. Malthoid oil paper was used for this job. The two men on the stack are (left to right) K. Gamble, the local school bus driver, and T. Ferrara who worked on the farm.

BA2479/55: My employer bought a "Commer" truck driven by Perkins D6 Diesel Engine. It was used for carting material where required and bringing fuel from Perth. The photo shows myself standing on top of a load of wool whilst waiting for the last bale.
BA2479/56: Another machine which my employer bought at this time was a TD 14A tractor and a 7 yard scoop from a chap in Badgebup. I went down with him to look at the plant.

BA2479/57: Late in 1953 I decided that it was about time I purchased my own transport. I bought an 8cwt "Commer" utility, prior to going on holidays early in 1954. I drove to a station known as Coburn. This station is a few kilometers south of Shark Bay.

BA2479/58: B.H.W. Johnston driving the D4 during hay baling. The tractor had to be driven slowly so that the baler was not over supplied with hay. This baler was driven by its own petrol driven V4 Wisconsin air cooled petrol engine. As the driver I was responsible fo
BA2479/59: Early in 1953 the employer purchased a Caterpillar D4 Crawler tractor. I drove this machine. The photo shoes the machine ready for a day's work.

BA2479/60: Some more plant which the employer had built by an engineering firm in Wagin as a Root Rake and Root Ripper. The ripper was hauled by the TD14 and the rake was hauled by the D4. Replacing a ripper tine was a back breaking job for 2 men.

BA2479/61: Early in 1955 I was employed to rake roots into windrows and piles ready for burning. Here again the tractor had to be slowly driven. This meant that the engine tended to become cold so an old rag was mounted to the front of the tractor. Another thing tha

BA2479/62: Roots about to be raked into the rake drum. When the operator was satisfied that there was enough roots in the rotating drum a small line connected to a trip lever in the rake caused a large hook mounted on each wheel to engage on a sprocket mounted on ea

BA2479/63: This photo shows roots ready for burning. Word about this method of land clearing spread because some gentlemen from Muntadgin visited the place and the saw how the job was done. They were very impressed. Muntadgin would be about 180kms from Kulin as one
BA2479/64: From 1943-1946 I served in the Royal Australian Navy
